My daughter wore her Little Mermaid Lithophane Pendant to school the other day and when she came home, she asked if I could make a pendant for other princesses. When I said I could, she pulled out a handwritten list of all the girls in her class with the princesses and colors that each girl wants for their pendants. I had to laugh. So, now I have created one for Cinderella and Belle. In the pictures, you can see the original picture and the black and white one that I did some drawing on to help create definition for the model. My camera phone does not do this justice. It looks much better. I used MakeALot's lithophane generator to create the lithophane: http://3dp.rocks/lithophane/ Then I imported it into Tinkercad to cut out the circle, put a round rim on it and a loop for hanging it. I also created some custom support to help hold it upright for printing. See the instructions for tips on printing.

I found that it works best with a plastic that is mostly opaque.  Transparent plastic does not have enough light resistance to define darks very well, but it does create an interesting look.  On the other end, plastic that is too opaque requires a lot of light to see the picture.  I included a picture with my white plastic which is quite opaque, pink in the middle and light blue transparent for an example.  
I printed this in a vertical orientation because you get a much better resolution than you can with printing lithophanes flat.  
If your bed moves on one of the axis, make sure that the model is oriented lengthwise along that axis. Mine moves along the Y axis which is why the model is oriented that way. use a raft to help secure it to the bed since it is so skinny, we want to make sure that it does not tip at all.  
I printed this at a slow speed of about 40mm/sec at .15mm layer height. I set the slicer to 8 perimeters. The reason for setting the perimeters so high is because you want it to print with all perimeters and little to no zig-zag infill. When you get a ways up in a skinny print like this, the quick zig-zag infill can shake the print loose a little, ruining the print.  
The support structure should break off cleanly and need very little cleanup.

I made this geodesic dome as my first experiment using Autodesk's 3DS Max Design 2011. I was inspired by Buckminster Fuller and his domes. I exported it to .STL and scaled it up in replicator-G to print on the Makerbot ToM with Stepstruder MK6. It took 45 minutes to print. You can see more images at: http://digitaltectonics.org/blog/?p=1052 I was worried that the top might collapse since there is no support material, but it held up.. The very top is a bit 'messy' and blended in, but it held up just fine. It is nice to see it build in rings getting smaller and smaller as it goes up.
Just build it! Maybe use it to stick toothpicks in and put it on the dinner table as a conversation piece.

A more or less parametric scad file that allows you to create hexagonal burr puzzles. In the current configuration, you can mostly enable or disable the various notches in a 12 piece setup (4 x 3 parallel bars) using a binary pattern - generating anything else requires a bit of twiddling with all kinds of parameters. But the hex bars and setup should provide a decent start. 
It also shows how to intrude faces in the hexagonal directions to increase the tolerance. 
An example is included how to create notched pieces. If you print the attached STL file three times, you should already be able to obtain a solvable puzzle. 
Public domain, because sharing is caring. Feel free to flattr me or impress me with your puzzle creations. :)

title: Aluminum swivel pulley cast in ABS mold

description.text: An attempt at a pre-assembled casting.

This aluminum swivel pulley was cast in an ABS mold. One inch wheel diameter, and should accommodate 1/4 inch rope.  
[ Update: An Alternate swivel style was uploaded by mistake. I left that one here (pulley_alternate.stl) and added the one used in this project (pulley.stl). Either one can be printed if someone wants a plastic pulley, and the wheel and axle fits either one.]  
Since pre-assembled parts are commonly 3D printed, I thought perhaps a mold could be printed where the cast metal parts would already be assembled.  
This pulley was a simple test. The swivel ring is cast within the pulley. When the mold is stripped off, the ring is (hopefully) free to swivel.  
I haven't bothered to cast the wheel yet since I'd probably redesign the whole thing if I actually intend to use it. It could have thicker sections for more strength.  
I suppose the pulley's wheel could be cast pre-assembled, but there has to be adequate space between the parts. Clearances around the axle should be minimal, so there's a conflict.   
An integrated wheel / axle could probably be cast, if it were worth the effort, but a nut and bolt is just so easy.  
,,,,,,,,,  
There have been lots of failures while experimenting lately. The timing pulley (see last 2 photos) was one of them. I just can't get it right despite a dozen attempts.  
A spectacular ball of flame erupted when I first tried casting the timing pulley by a different method. The aluminum was poured way too hot, while the mold was spinning at 2000 RPM. The smoke reached its ignition point, and went poof.  
That's when I considered abandoning this whole aluminum casting thing. But the feeling went away after a couple hours, when the shakes wore off. It was just a wake-up call... Don't get cocky.

title: SPK-AZ1 Flat Lens Modifier (requires 40 mm UV photographic filter)

description.text:
NEW Version 2 has been posted
One of the biggest disappointments of the Sony HDR-AZ1 is the fact that there is no flat lens mount or flat lens underwater housing. With the current SPK-AZ1 it is all but unusable underwater since the curved lens results in out of focus video despite the high quality of the Zeiss lens. This adapter helps correct that.  
The back side of the flat lens will sit approximately 1.5 mm away from the front of the HDR-AZ1 camera lens.  
See instruction page for more information and required hardware.
STEP file included with version 2 for anyone that wants to modify it themselves.

Please DO NOT print this using PLA as we want to maintain the waterproof nature of the SPK-AZ1. What you need for this is two additional items. the first is some 3M waterproof double-sided tape or equivalent, something like 3M VHB 4926 which is available in 1.5" discs from places like Digikey. A cheap 40 mm video camera UV filter from eBay. You must make certain that the glass can be removed from the metal housing of the filter. Installation
Carefully press the front lens of the SPK-AZ1 from the inside toward the outside to break the seal of the existing adhesive. You can press fairly hard since it is a glass lens. Once the convex lens is removed, clean off all the remaining tape residue from the face of the housing. place a circle of the 3M tape where the existing tape used to be. Remove the upper protective layer from the tape and press the modifier (this piece you are looking at right now) in firmly. Place another circle of tape in the top edge of the modifier and set it aside. Take you UV filter and unscrew the housing parts to remove the actual optical glass. Make sure it is cleaned on all sides. Go back to the housing and remove the backing from the tape and firmly press in the UV glass filter. Set the whole unit aside to allow the adhesive to set. Note: Do this mod at your own risk, I make no guarantees as to the usefulness of this modification. In my case is works, YMMV.

description.text:
EDIT (4/6/2015): Added Logo and non-logo versions of the body (V1.1) which feature the following improvements:
  • Removed mag tab, it was useless, weak, and made a raft a necessity (though looked cool)
  • Variable radius edge blend inside mag area to help printing
  • Reduced length where back of cartridge goes by 0.5mm to help feeding issues observed in Lancer AW mags. Old ram still works.

    Introducing the beginning of my 5th generation of modeling! These parts feature full parametrization (unfortunately for TV users, not OpenSCAD) and awesome renders! This is my first attempt at a parameterized model and it has turned out great! This was an awesome learning experience, simple enough to not get too bogged down, yet complex enough to be more useful than a box.

    • Unfortunately Thingiverse doesn't support TIF apparently, so I had to convert to PNG.

Key Features:
  • Slimmed down sexier version of source file
  • Easily adapted to .308 or any other caliber
  • Chamfered entrance for increased ease of use
    • I also posted the version with my school's rifle team logo on it! (Special thanks to our webmaster/GFX guy) Now we can load our mags at competitions with logos on our shirts AND 3D printed mag loaders. Totally more impressive than any other team.

Fun Facts about the AR-15:
  • Despite some lawmakers opinions in hippie states, there is PLENTY of sporting purpose in an AR-15, they are my school rifle team's go to gun because it is lightweight, accurate, and low powered, thus controllable.
  • AR stands for "Armalite Rifle" not "Assault Rifle" after the original company that produced it back in the day. The semi-auto civilian versions are SPORTING RIFLES not so called "assault rifles". Police and the military get the fully-automatic (select-fire) assault rifles.
  • It's attraction to millions of competition and recreational shooters alike is the light weight, accuracy, and low power, making it easy to control. (Really trying to hammer home the fact that despite some media know-it-alls claims, it is very weak as far as rifles go. It is too weak to be used to hunt deer in some states) It is also fully modular and has a variety of standards to ensure parts and accessories from other rifles will be universally compatible with all AR platform guns of the same caliber. It is this property that has caused it to be the most popular rifle to make 3D printed accessories for.

Got dimensions of other magazine loader and wanted to port to new software as a learning experience.  The goal was to make it use less material while also looking nicer.  It should function just as well or better than the source file (had issues with Lancer AWM magazines).  
Print 100% infill, .1-.2 layer height.

comments.text: I have made at least 5 of these for myself, and friends/family as gifts. They work quite well and despite the name saying it only holds 5, they hold 6 at a time. So five times loading with this and you fill a 30-round mag pretty quickly. I print them with 40% infill and supports (in PLA). After quite a bit of use they seem to be holding up quite well.

description.text:
I am still in love with my ancient Trust Soundwave 20 loudspeakers. They are standing on a metal bracket. This bracket can also be inserted in the top of the speakers so they can be hang. To maximize desk space, I decided to design mounts for exactly that.
I used Tinkercad for this mount: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/3yigCNPUhAH-loudspeaker-mount-for-trust-soundwave-20
Print six of the mounts. When mounting the brackets, keep in mind that you have to squeeze the metal brackets somewhat to insert them in the loudspeakers.

Because wall-mounts cost around 20-30€ I designed one myself. Weight is around 20-40g (depending on the infill), so it's quite a lot cheaper.
This mount can be slided onto a hexagonal bolt screwed into the wall. Uploaded two versions: one with bigger clamps and one with smaller (but wobblier) ones The gap were the hexagonal screw head slides in is 11mm wide. The thread has to be smaller than 5mm in diameter.

description.text:

Looking for a machined lead screw, I saw a 400mm long 8mm SDS drill bit hanging behind the counter. Got me thinking... The attached lead screw nut is scripted in Openscad to fit the Alpen F4 forte 8mm L450/400mm SDS-plus dril bit. I cut off the cutting tip, and threaded on the nuts. Looks very promising... UPDATE:

title: i3 in a Box - Joe's RepRap

description.text:
I designed this printer to get a very rigid and easy boxable construction without any too complicated mechanics. I used many parts of my old Prusa i3 - so basically, it's an i3 with a 2020 aluminium frame inspired by Haeckel, and most of the Prusa i3 x or y-Axis parts will fit. This one uses 8mm trapezoid threaded rods with 17mm nuts, feel free to build it with any other i3 x-ends. The X-carriage is a modified version of clefranc's Universal X-Carriage: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:97719
Just added a small piece to hit the endstop switch. I like ffleurey's direct drive extruder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:147705 download it there or use any Prusa i3 extruder you like, or use a bowden setup as shown in the second picture. For endstops, I'm using some like these, or just be creative:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037870
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:30085
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:85368 Print space (depending on extruder design) is 200x200x210mm, with enough clearance on x-axis to add a dual extruder. Anyway, dimensions are easy to vary by the lenght of the aluminium extrusions. *Update 22 April '15: Some minor changes...
  • clearance to insert TR8 Nuts
  • made belt guides a bit wider
  • made tensioners wider
  • 3-way-connector is now more printable and has more clearance
    • *Update 19 Aug '15: Changed length of the extrusions. 430mm just wasn't enough for Y-direction! *Update 09 Okt '15: Uploaded a new version of the bearing clips and a belt holder with tree holes for the printbed. Seems like the drawing I referred to was a quite old one, these should fit much better. *Update 25 Okt '15: Added/modified the x-carriage, new picture

For frame Assembly, refer to Haeckel building instructions: http://reprap.org/wiki/Haeckel
Most of the rest is Prusa i3 stuff, just make sure that everything is assembled in 90° angles. So how many parts do you have to print? 8 edge
4 3-way-connector
4 belt_guide
4 Y_rod_holder
3 bearing_clip_LM8UU
2 motor_mount_Z
2 axis_holder_Z
2 spool_holder (optional)
1 of all the rest Stuff you need: 16 20x20mm aluminium extrusions, 450mm length (420mm will do for the 4 upright ones, but longer means higher build space).
~110 slot-nuts for the aluminium extrusions + bolts, or use standart M4 nuts with these instead: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1061769
2 ball bearings, SKF 623 (3x10x4mm) for belt idling
2 8mm leadscrews/trapezoid threaded rods, length ~340mm
2 nuts for leadscrews, TR8x1,5 SW17
4 smooth rods 8mm for x and y-axis, same length as the aluminium extrusions
2 smooth rods 8mm for z-axis, ~360mm long
2 Couplers 5 to 8mm for Z leadscrews to motors (Nema 17) OR use those leadscrew stepper motors.
1 Prusa i3 Y-Carriage and things you use for any other i3, like stepper motors, GT2 belt + pulleys, lots of M3/M4 bolts + nuts, and electronics.
Also, dont't forget to print some endstop holders and extruder parts. I'd be happy to see some builds!

When it shuts the sleeve is pulled back into a collar, which then it compresses the sleeve due to the collar only making its way the the very edge of the inner sleeve to grip the nylon cylinder  
What is needed to just to finish the 3d design, is that i'm struggling to make a spring that will fit in between the collar and the inner tool sleeve, then a lid to stop the spring from coming out under compression.  
The hole i made was to fit a 5 mm mill bit so i made the hole 6mm and made the slits 1 mm, I also tried to calculate the radius for the collar and how far down it would go to close the gap.  
the shaft is 5 mm I diameter i don't know much about spindles on the machine as i'm not at the stage of building one yet but the added idea was if the spindle went in clockwise direction then the inner collaiter, spring  and collar would be made from titanium and the shaft would be made from a magnetic material so i can put a electromagnet on the shaft, the shaft would have a anti clockwise thread  on to screw the rest of the assembly,  
The tool bits would be in a home position on the machine and referenced as how many tool heads the machine can handle(uncertain on the programming side), but the tool bit will be in a cup standing vertical, the diameter of the cup will match the the collar diameter but not the inner coliater allowing it to drop or pick up the tool bit. the electric magnet will operate at the same time when it goes to drop it will turn off, only problem i can see in using a electromagnet is resident of the magnetism would it drop the tool, other option is making the shaft hollow enough to create a vacuum, but hey its up too you guys to take it further i will take it further myself even with your help when it comes time to build my cnc mill

description.text: I wanted to see my TOM doing its job and holding a flashlight got old pretty fast, so I decide to install LED lighting. I bought an adhesive backed cool white SMD LED strip at Amazon (I am sure there are cheaper alternatives out there but Amazon is "reasonable" and fast) ( http://www.amazon.com/Flexible-Lighting-LED-Ribbon-2026wh/dp/B002QQ1YOM/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1301971588&sr=8-1 ) and its matching PWM (Pulse Width Modulation) dimming control ( http://www.amazon.com/Dimming-Controller-Lights-Ribbon-Volt/dp/B003L4KKF2/ref=pd_cp_hi_2 ).

The LED strip can be cut every 3rd LED and after removing the protective material can be soldered again (very well marked + and - ), so I cut 5 pieces and glued it to a piece of cardboard cut to match the Z-Stage. Soldered the connections and attached a long black and yellow wire (to match the 12V color used in the power supply). The cardboard is held in place by the 2 plastruder thumbscrews and a 3rd screw on the back.
I also attached one long strip (circa 50 leds) to the inside of the TOM front plate again soldered pieces of black and yellow wire to it. 
I took the PWM out of the case and printed a bracket for it (designed in SketchUp as I am too old to learn Blender :) ). The potentiometer was installed on the unused hole for the front right Z-rod.
The 12 V comes for a spare connector in the power supply (black and yellow). I installed some pins on the PWM connector so I could keep the original connector on the 12V power supply.
The wires are still in a bit of a mess, but I will get some brackets to get them under control and out of the way soon.
The whole thing works really well. I will probably get a more rigid cardboard for the Z-stage ( or maybe just use double sided tape) and stick a few more LEDS in it. All together I may have used 75 of the 300 LEDs that came in the roll.

Depending on the type of PLA/ABS you use, you might need to paint the probe with e.g. a black Edding. This makes sure no light gets through it.

description.text:
Robotic quadruped designed for educational electronics environments. Remixed from @TheCase Mini Quadruped - optimized for 9G servos.
The parts of the robot is 3dprinter-friendly, use "micro servo 9g" specifically designed to work with cheap servos "TowerPro". Still, you can adjust the dimensions thereof to suit the needs. Some modifications are:
  • Solid chassis.
  • Added base for batteries and Arduino.
  • Side opening for easy mounting of the servo.
  • Restrain for the servo horn.
  • Modified tolerances to minimize post-processing.
  • Added bases in the legs to use self adhesive rubber buttons, to improve grip.
    • Designed to be controlled from Scratch by Arduino, all sources: https://github.com/tallerinventores/educational-robot-quadruped

• Print (8x servo_button; 8x shoulder; 4x leg; 1x tray; 1x arduino_base; 1x chassis).
  • Screw the four servos to the chassis using two servo screws.
  • Screw a servo on each leg using two servo screws.
  • Screw pairs of shoulders using two M3x6 screws. (recomended: do not use washers, only a nut per screw).
  • For each shoulder: Places servo horn and servo button inside shoulder. Then fit the servo on the shoulder and screw the servo horn to the servo using servo screws. Make sure the servo is in the correct position and can perform all the way.
  • Press the tray against the chassis until it clicks.
  • Screw Arduino base on the tray using two M3x35 screws. (recomended: do not use washers, only a nut per screw). Between the tray and the Arduino base must be placed the battery holder.
  • Screw the Arduino up the Arduino base using four M3x10 screws. (recomended: do not use washers, only a nut per screw).
  • Program and enjoy it.
